{"key":"post-12760395","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12760395</id>\n<content>This is exactly the dilemma commercial mushroom farms face.&amp;nbsp; If you work fast, you can do four to five &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Grain-to-Grain-Transfers&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;grain to grain transfers&lt;/a&gt;, before &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Horse-Manure-Substrate&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;spawning to bulk&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp; This will easily fill a small warehouse with grain spawn.&amp;nbsp; You can then refrigerate it until ready to use.&amp;nbsp; When you get low, simply start the process over again, ensuring you don't run out before the next batch of spawn is ready.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Obviously, you'll want to learn to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Agar-Petri-Dishes&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;work with agar&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Strain-Isolation&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;isolate strains&lt;/a&gt; and store the cultures in &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Master-Culture-Slants&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;master culture slants&lt;/a&gt; to keep good genetics.&amp;nbsp; You wouldn't want to start from spores each time and have your hard work based on a roll of the genetic dice.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12760570</next>\n<prev>12759695</prev>\n<first>12758874</first>\n<last>12783245</last>\n<when>1276830143</when>\n<utime>06/18/10 06:02 AM</utime>\n</post>"}